    "id": "system-walkthroughs-debugging",
    "title": "The System Walkthrough Has Become My New Debugging Session",
    "date": "2026-06-21T00:00:00.000Z",
    "readTime": "3 min read",
    "category": "AI-Native Engineering",
    "summary": "A coding agent built my project end-to-end and every test passed, but I still felt disconnected from the system. Walking through it like a user became the way I rebuild understanding when implementation gets delegated to AI.",
    "content": "\nI’ve seen Addy’s articles pop up online a lot lately. When I found his LinkedIn course AI-Native Engineer Foundations, I clicked to check it out. I’ve been exploring AI-native engineering on my own recently, so I was curious what the course covered.\n\nNot long ago, I used a coding agent to build a full project end-to-end. It wrote the unit tests, handled deployment, and fixed several issues that showed up during testing and launch. All tests passed and the deployment ran smoothly. Even so, I felt disconnected from the whole system afterwards. I hadn’t built the same level of understanding I normally would have from implementing it myself. I knew the system worked, but I wasn’t yet confident I understood how all the pieces fit together.\n\nI went through the entire system step by step to understand what had actually been built. I used the UI like a regular end user, checked every backend service, double-checked stored data, and made sure logs and traces were all set up correctly. Going through the whole system like this is how I double-check all the code the AI builds for me.\n\nTo put it simply:\n\n> The system walkthrough has become my new debugging session.\n\nThat disconnected feeling made me rethink how developer knowledge gets built with AI tools. Before coding agents, we spent lots of time working through logic, debugging problems, fixing errors, and wiring all system components together. We naturally learned the ins and outs of a system through hands-on implementation work. Now AI handles most of that build work, so our daily focus has shifted.\n\nThese days, we spend more time writing clear requirements, setting up environments for coding agents, setting up evaluations, checking AI-generated output, and walking through full systems to fully grasp what’s been built.\n\nThe course helped me realize that AI-native engineering isn’t just about using coding agents. It’s about changing how we build system understanding when most implementation work gets delegated to AI.\n\nBefore AI, understanding came from writing and fixing code ourselves.\n\nNow we can hand implementation work to AI, but we can’t hand off the work of truly understanding the system.\n\nThis also helped me understand Addy's 70/30 rule. AI can take over much of the implementation work, but engineers still own architecture, security, edge cases, business requirements, and system understanding.\n\nAI can generate the implementation. Understanding the system is still our job.\n",
    "contentHtml": "<p>I’ve seen Addy’s articles pop up online a lot lately. When I found his LinkedIn course AI-Native Engineer Foundations, I clicked to check it out. I’ve been exploring AI-native engineering on my own recently, so I was curious what the course covered.</p>\n<p>Not long ago, I used a coding agent to build a full project end-to-end. It wrote the unit tests, handled deployment, and fixed several issues that showed up during testing and launch. All tests passed and the deployment ran smoothly. Even so, I felt disconnected from the whole system afterwards. I hadn’t built the same level of understanding I normally would have from implementing it myself. I knew the system worked, but I wasn’t yet confident I understood how all the pieces fit together.</p>\n<p>I went through the entire system step by step to understand what had actually been built. I used the UI like a regular end user, checked every backend service, double-checked stored data, and made sure logs and traces were all set up correctly. Going through the whole system like this is how I double-check all the code the AI builds for me.</p>\n<p>To put it simply:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The system walkthrough has become my new debugging session.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That disconnected feeling made me rethink how developer knowledge gets built with AI tools. Before coding agents, we spent lots of time working through logic, debugging problems, fixing errors, and wiring all system components together. We naturally learned the ins and outs of a system through hands-on implementation work. Now AI handles most of that build work, so our daily focus has shifted.</p>\n<p>These days, we spend more time writing clear requirements, setting up environments for coding agents, setting up evaluations, checking AI-generated output, and walking through full systems to fully grasp what’s been built.</p>\n<p>The course helped me realize that AI-native engineering isn’t just about using coding agents. It’s about changing how we build system understanding when most implementation work gets delegated to AI.</p>\n<p>Before AI, understanding came from writing and fixing code ourselves.</p>\n<p>Now we can hand implementation work to AI, but we can’t hand off the work of truly understanding the system.</p>\n<p>This also helped me understand Addy&#39;s 70/30 rule. AI can take over much of the implementation work, but engineers still own architecture, security, edge cases, business requirements, and system understanding.</p>\n<p>AI can generate the implementation. Understanding the system is still our job.</p>\n",
